        <hl1>The President and Intelligent Design</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush Remarks Roil Debate Over Teaching of Evolution'' (news article, Aug. 3):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush Remarks Roil Debate Over Teaching of Evolution'' (news article, Aug. 3):</p>
        <p>President Bush, in suggesting that there should be time given over to teach intelligent design, continues to display a shameful degree of science illiteracy, consistent with his attitudes toward global warming and stem cell research.</p>
        <p>His anti-science bias has done more to diminish the office of the presidency than of anyone in memory. It is in shocking contrast with the early days of our Republic, when science-minded political leaders like Thomas Jefferson held sway.</p>
        <p>A.R. Liboff  Rochester, Mich., Aug. 3, 2005</p>
        <p>The writer is professor emeritus of physics, Oakland University.</p>
      </block>
